[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] The **10th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the Senate and the House of Representatives.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from March 4, 1807, to March 4, 1809, during the seventh and eighth years of Thomas Jefferson's presidency.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1800 census; both chambers had an overwhelming Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed in order of seniority, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their district numbers.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] There were 5 resignations, 2 deaths, and 1 interim appointment.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Of the voting members, there were 4 resignations, 4 deaths, and 2 vacancies from the beginning of this Congress.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Democratic-Republicans had no net change and Federalists picked up 2 seats.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/11th-united-states-congress] The **11th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/11th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from March 4, 1809, to March 4, 1811, during the first two years of James Madison's presidency.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/11th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1800 United States census.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/11th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/11th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/11th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1814; Class 2 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1810; and Class 3 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1812.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/11th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their districts.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/11th-united-states-congress] There were 8 resignations, 2 deaths, 1 interim appointment, and 1 vacancy from before this Congress.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/11th-united-states-congress] Of the voting members, there were 12 resignations, 1 death, and 1 change due to a contested election.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/12th-united-states-congress] The **12th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/12th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C. from March 4, 1811, to March 4, 1813, during the third and fourth years of James Madison's presidency.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/12th-united-states-congress] During this congress, two new Senate seats were added for the new state of Louisiana.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/12th-united-states-congress] During this congress, one new House seat was added for the new state of Louisiana.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/13th-united-states-congress] The **13th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/13th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C. from March 4, 1813, to March 4, 1815, during the fifth and sixth years of James Madison's presidency.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/13th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1810 United States census.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/13th-united-states-congress] The first two sessions were held at the Capitol building while the third, convened after the Burning of Washington, took place in the First Patent Building.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/13th-united-states-congress] Following the 1810 census, the size of the House was increased to 182 seats from 142.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/13th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring reelection in 1814; Class 2 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring reelection in 1816; and Class 3 meant their term began in this Congress, requiring reelection in 1818.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/14th-united-states-congress] The **14th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/14th-united-states-congress] It met in the Old Brick Capitol in Washington, D.C. from March 4, 1815, to March 3, 1817, during the seventh and eighth years of James Madison's presidency.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/14th-united-states-congress] During this congress, two Senate seats were added for the new state of Indiana.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/14th-united-states-congress] During this congress, one House seat was added for the new state of Indiana.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/14th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class and representatives are listed by district.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/14th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1820; Class 2 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1816; and Class 3 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1818.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] The **15th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] It met in the Old Brick Capitol in Washington, D.C. from March 4, 1817, to March 4, 1819, during the first two years of James Monroe's presidency.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Two major treaties with the United Kingdom were approved, finalized and signed during the 15th Congress, both the Rush–Bagot Treaty and the Treaty of 1818, both of which pertained to the United States-Canada border, and both of which were overwhelmingly popular in the United States.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] President James Monroe and Secretary of State John Quincy Adams were credited with the accomplishments.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] The letter also attacked King Louis XVIII of France for insulting remarks he had made towards American diplomats and about the United States, as well as his refusal to pay reparations owed to the United States from damages incurred during the Quasi-War.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] The letter was signed in December 1818 by Joel Abbot, Thomas W.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Hall, Jesse Slocumb, James Owen, Weldon Nathaniel Edwards, James Stewart, James Strudwick Smith, Thomas Settle, George Mumford, Daniel Munroe Forney, Felix Walker, Lewis Williams, John J.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Marr, George Poindexter, Prentiss Mellen, Harrison Gray Otis, Enoch Lincoln, Jonathan Mason, Nathaniel Silsbee, Jeremiah Nelson, Timothy Fuller, Elijah H.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Several governors also signed the letter, which was entirely symbolic and intended as a gesture of goodwill, including Gabriel Slaughter, William Rabun, John Geddes, John Branch, John Brooks, James Patton Preston and David Holmes.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] This was significant because the governors and the members of congress were from different regions (both Massachusetts and several southern states were represented), and because signers came from both the Whig Party and the Democratic-Republicans.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Many members of congress and Washington DC had a very hostile relationship with France's notoriously combative ambassador Jean-Guillaume, baron Hyde de Neuville, which contributed to the letters contents as per France.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] During this congress, two Senate seats were added for each of the new states of Mississippi and Illinois.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] During this congress, one House seat was added for each of the new states of Mississippi and Illinois.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/15th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1820; Class 2 meant their term began with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1822; and Class 3 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1818.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/16th-united-states-congress] The **16th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/16th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C. from March 4, 1819, to March 4, 1821, during the third and fourth years of James Monroe's presidency.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/16th-united-states-congress] During this congress, two Senate seats were added for each of the new states of Alabama and Maine.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/16th-united-states-congress] During this congress, one House seat was added for the new state of Alabama and one seat was reapportioned from Massachusetts to the new state of Maine.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/16th-united-states-congress] For the beginning of the next congress, six more seats from Massachusetts would be reapportioned to Maine.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/16th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1820; Class 2 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1822; and Class 3 meant their term began in this Congress, requiring re-election in 1824.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/16th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of this Congress.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/16th-united-states-congress] There were 5 resignations, 2 deaths, 2 vacancies before the Congress, and 4 new seats.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/16th-united-states-congress] The Democratic-Republicans had a 7-seat net gain and the Federalists had a 1-seat net loss.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/16th-united-states-congress] There were 13 resignations, 5 deaths, 2 contested elections, and 2 new seats.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/16th-united-states-congress] The Democratic-Republicans had a 1-seat net gain and the Federalists had no net change.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/united-states-house-committee-on-elections] The **United States House Committee on Elections** is a former standing committee of the United States House of Representatives.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/united-states-house-committee-on-elections] From 1789 until the mid-19th century the number of contested election cases remained stable at an average of three per Congress.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/united-states-house-committee-on-elections] After the 34th Congress (1855–57) the number of contested seats rose sporadically to a peak of 38 during the 54th Congress (1895–97).
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/united-states-house-committee-on-elections] In 1895, due to the increase in workload, the committee was split into three separate committees: Elections #1, Elections #2, and Elections #3.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/united-states-house-committee-on-elections] After 1935 the number of contested elections returned to an average of three per Congress, and in 1947 the three Elections Committees were abolished and their jurisdiction included in that of the new House Administration Committee.
[src:united-states-house-committee-on-elections/united-states-house-committee-on-elections] In November 2018, Nancy Pelosi announced her intention to restore the Elections Subcommittee of the Committee on House Administration in the 116th Congress and name Congresswoman Marcia L.
